{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"099c9a66-3c0b-4cad-b89c-98a4165d0a8f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `kubectl cp` to copy the trace file out of the pod.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container).\n- For a flamegraph-ready format, add `--format speedscope`.\n- If you need OS-level context (native frames, kernel), use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --clreventlevel verbose` or fall back to **`perf`** (`perf record -g -p <PID>`), but `dotnet-trace` is usually sufficient and much simpler.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3ec58e8e-b95e-45bd-81e2-bba3518f297c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":371},"id":"42a30c24-b839-4b99-bd24-e942f1fd54c1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:53:01.170Z","parentId":"eea0bf6f-d540-443a-92f1-d478691403ea"}
